 Synchronous programming is a programming style where one operation waits for another to complete before proceeding with its execution. In this model, all code runs sequentially, and the program moves forward only when the current action has been completed. An example in JavaScript would be:

```javascript
function greet() {
  console.log("Hello");
}

function wish() {
  console.log("Good morning!");
}

greet();
wish();
```

In this example, the "greet" function is called first, and then the "wish" function is executed. Both functions are executed one after another in a sequential manner, waiting for each other to complete before moving forward.

Asynchronous programming, on the other hand, allows operations to execute concurrently without waiting for each other to finish. This is achieved by using callbacks or promises, which allow the execution of code once an asynchronous operation has completed. An example in JavaScript would be:

```javascript
function greet() {
  console.log("Hello");
}

function wish(callback) {
  setTimeout(() => {
    console.log("Good morning!");
    callback();
  }, 1000);
}

greet();
wish(function () {
  console.log("Wow, it's a beautiful day!");
});
```

In this example, the "greet" function is called first and executed immediately. The "wish" function takes a callback as an argument. Inside the "wish" function, we use setTimeout to execute the code after 1 second has passed. Once the setTimeout expires, it logs "Good morning!" and executes the callback provided, which is the code inside the function passed as an argument (i.e., "Wow, it's a beautiful day!"). This allows both functions to run concurrently without waiting for each other, providing a non-blocking and asynchronous execution model.

